comments.body:
@sipa Yes, that seems to be the bulk of them.

~I can't figure out why this _isn't_ UB (from ParseScript()):~
```c++
    if (Func("pkh", expr)) {
        auto pubkey = ParsePubkey(key_exp_index, expr, ctx != ParseScriptContext::P2WSH, out, error);
```
~Remember that ```Func()``` takes a ```std::string```, not a c string. So in the example above, presumably ```expr``` ends up pointing to somewhere inside the temporary string's memory after ```Func()``` returns. As you [pointed out](https://github.com/bitcoin/bitcoin/pull/18468#discussion_r443000807), for string literals that's the lifetime of the program. But in this case, I think we're relying on the fact that std::string's .data() returns that exact pointer. Is that guaranteed to be the case?~

Edit: Nevermind. Guess I read the body of ```Func()``` too quickly. The modified span is not created from the string param.
